This is the main script of the Microbial AmpLicon AnalYses (MAnAnAs) workflow to analyse high-throughput sequencing data, invoking all other scripts.

Short instructions

MAnAnAs (Microbial AmpLicon AnalYses) is a workflow compiled of Rmarkdown scripts to visualise and statistically analyse high-throughput amplicon sequencing data (bacterial 16S and fungal ITS sequences). Most of the scripts build further from the package phyloseq, and hulp packages of Bioconductor and DADA2. To get started click on the menus on the left.

Five steps to get started

  1. You need RStudio, and R-version 3.6.2 for windows, or R-version 3.6.3 for Mac. Execute the RStudio.exe, and also R3.6.2.exe, using the default settings. Another program you want to install is notepad++, you need this to easily see and read .R files.

  2. Make a folder called Mananas in C:/Users/yourname/Documents. In this folder, place the provided script Initialise.R and the Man_02_362.zip file. Unzip(MAS_win362.zip) and place in your Mananas folder.

  3. Go to the Mananas folder that you created in step 2. Right click on the file Initialise.R and open with Rstudio. In RStudio, please first check if you are using R 3.6.2 version. For this click, Tools > Global Options > and in the pop-up screen select 64-bit, R 3.6.2. Click Apply, Ok. Now you are ready to run initialise.R

  4. Follow the instructions in the Initialise.R file and execute all steps.
    The last command renv:restore can take 1 hour because it will auto-install all packages, in the meantime you can watch this 15 min video to learn R.

  5. You are now ready to run the scripts and generate graphs! Go to your Mananas folder, and click Mananas.Rproj to open. It is good to first test your install by running the scripts on the Minimal Reproducible Example (MRE) dataset (click on the left pannel submenus). When you have practised how it works, you can generate a folder in C:/Users/yourname/Documents/yourname and make the following three subfolders:
    Input: Here you need to put your otu_table.txt and mapping.txt and optionally phylogenetic tree, obtained after running Dada2 (or similar).
    Config: place here the config.yaml file
    Results: Here the results will be auto-written too. Make sure your path is not too long; then png will throw an error
    Update the config file with the new paths to your input, config, results folders, and customise the config.yaml file for your needs.
    **Hints: to help you structuring your thoughts, and filling in the yaml options file, make for yourself an infographic to visually represent your research questions, and datamatrix. See for examples, the template infographic_template.xlsx in the folder Mananas/templates.

Configuration

Clean workspace

rm(list=ls()) # remove all objects from your workspace, start clean
     options(warn=-1) # toggle off warnings

Open Mananas project

Go to your mananas folder in C:/Documents/User/yourname/Mananas, and click Mananas.Rproj to open. Now your console should say something like: Project C:/Users/lucg6943/Documents/Mananas loaded. [renv 0.10.0].

Snapshot

To be sure, we run renv::snapshot to see if the lock file is in sync with your project. If it wants to update some things, say y.

renv::settings$snapshot.type("all")
     renv::snapshot()

Load libraries

### libraries
     library(yaml)
     library(icesTAF)
     library(rmarkdown)
     library(renv)

Define the path to your configuration folder

The configuration folder contains the config.yaml file. This file contains all the settings, custom options to run the scripts. So you need to edit this config file with the settings you like.

### Adapt the path to the configuration folder.
     Configuration_file_dir <- "C:/Users/lucg6943/Desktop/anvio_shared/Mananas2_36/MRE/Config"  # adapt this path to your configuration folder. Here we test it on the Minimal Reproducible Example (MRE), you find it in your Mananas folder.

Load the config.yaml file (run always)

The two lines below load in your configuration file (config.yaml). You need to adapt the name of the file below to the name of your config.yaml file. In this example, the name is config_MvH1.yaml, you find it in the mananas folder > MRE > config.

setwd(Configuration_file_dir)
     config = yaml.load_file("./config_MvH1.yaml")  # you can make different .yaml config files with different settings

From raw reads to amplicon sequence variance table (DADA2)

The first step to analyse NGS reads is to preprocess the raw reads to obtain a table of sequences/reads abundances per sample. This step can take (really) long (24h), so I will run it on the supercomputer, and provide you the results; otu_table.txt, and mapping.txt,
More info dada2 pipeline tutorial. More info about vsc. I am using UHasselt Tier-2 hardware, cluster Thinking7 (ProLiant DL380 Gen9 x84_64; CentOS 7.6.1810; haswell; ppn=24; pmem=5)) or cluster Genius (ProLiant DL380 Gen10 x86_64; CentOS 7.6.1810; skylake; ppn=36; pmem=5) (with different QC configurations).

Preprocessing

This is a very important step. All other scripts go further from this. Here you look at your dataset, and you can do supervised, or unsupervised filtering and trimming. Compare with the blank, and mocks, and take decissions of which ASVs you filter etc..Note that Preprocessing needs to have been run, before any other downstream analyses can be possibly run.

setwd(config$scripts_dir_local)
     rmarkdown::render("./Preprocessing/Preprocessing.Rmd",output_file = paste(config$results_dir_local, "/Pre_processing_", Sys.Date(), sep=''))

Alpha-diversity

Runs alpha-diversity: richness, shannon, simpson diversity, difference within your samples. The input is here the least filtered file from preprocessing: physeq_dc_sf.rds.

setwd(config$scripts_dir_local)
     rmarkdown::render('./Alpha/Alpha.Rmd',output_file = paste(config$results_dir_local, "/alpha_", Sys.Date(), sep=''))

Beta-diversity

Runs beta-diversity: difference between samples and shows results in a 2-D ordination plot (different methods: PCA, PcoA, nMDS, MDS, and various distances: Bray_curtis, weighted unifrac, unweighted unifrac)

setwd(config$scripts_dir_local)
     rmarkdown::render('./Beta/Beta_ordination.Rmd',output_file = paste(config$results_dir_local, "/beta_", Sys.Date(), sep=''))

Barcharts

Plots relative abundance barcharts (normal, facetted, and with statistics). You may want to assign custom colors:
Chroma.js Color Palette Helper
VIZ Palette
General tips, colorblind safe
How to give custom colors: edit the file function_barcharts_colors.R in the local directory: C:/Users/Documents/Mananas > Scripts > Barcharts

# Normal barcharts
     setwd(config$scripts_dir_local)
     rmarkdown::render('./Barcharts/Barcharts.Rmd',output_file = paste(config$results_dir_local, "/barcharts_", Sys.Date(), sep=''))
     
     # Facetted barcharts
     setwd(config$scripts_dir_local)
     rmarkdown::render('./Barcharts/Barcharts_facet.Rmd',output_file = paste(config$results_dir_local, "/barcharts_facet_", Sys.Date(), sep=''))
     
     # with statistics
     setwd(config$scripts_dir_local)
     rmarkdown::render('./Barcharts/Barcharts_stats.Rmd',output_file = paste(config$results_dir_local, "/barcharts_stats_", Sys.Date(), sep=''))

Bubbleplots

Plots a bubbleplot, with the size of the bubble the species relative abundance, and the color of the bubble, log2foldchange compared to a reference group.

setwd(config$scripts_dir_local)
     rmarkdown::render('./Bubbleplots/Bubbleplots.Rmd',output_file = paste(config$results_dir_local, "/bubbleplots_", Sys.Date(), sep=''))

Heatmaps

Plots a heatmap and hierarchical clustering of your samples.

setwd(config$scripts_dir_local)
     rmarkdown::render('./Heatmap/Heatmap.Rmd',output_file = paste(config$results_dir_local, "/heatmaps_", Sys.Date(), sep=''))

Differential abundance

Diffabundance 1 runs Deseq2 to identify differentially abundant ASVs between 2 groups and shows the results in a volcano plot.
Diffabundance 2 runs besides Deseq2, other statistical models, EdgeR, Limma, metagenomeseq, npseq, Aldex2 to identify differentially abudant ASVs between 2 groups. You have to iteratively run, and change/see the effect of alpha-cutoff, and log2foldchange cutoff settings. If nothing is significant, you get this error (thus increase alpha), or toggle off: Error in .local(object, , value) : all(!is.na(value)) is not TRUE

#Diffabundance 1
     setwd(config$scripts_dir_local)
     rmarkdown::render('./Diffabund/diffabund1.Rmd',output_file = paste(config$results_dir_local, "/diffabund1_", Sys.Date(), sep=''))
     
     # diffabundance 2
     setwd(config$scripts_dir_local)
     rmarkdown::render('./Diffabund/diffabund2.Rmd',output_file = paste(config$results_dir_local, "/diffabund2_", Sys.Date(), sep=''))

Venn diagram

Makes a venn diagram and shows shared and unique ASVs between up to 4 groups.

setwd(config$scripts_dir_local)
     rmarkdown::render('./Venn/venn.Rmd',output_file = paste(config$results_dir_local, "/Venn_", Sys.Date(), sep=''))

Factor analyses

Functional prediction

This assumes you have submitted your otu-tables and seq.fna files to Piphillin server, Picrust2, or Faptrotax. You need to reformat the input/output files (a lot). Therefore I have made an automated script for this: Functional_prediction.pbs (compiled of basic unix commands, python and perl scripts). Result is the input file: function_table.txt which can be loaded in and run.

# Load and preprocess function table
     setwd(config$scripts_dir_local)
     rmarkdown::render("./Preprocessing/Preprocessing_fp.Rmd",output_file = paste(config$results_dir_local, "/Pre_processing_fp", Sys.Date(), sep=''))
     
     # Normal Barcharts
     setwd(config$scripts_dir_local)
     rmarkdown::render('./Barcharts/Barcharts_fp.Rmd',output_file = paste(config$results_dir_local, "/barcharts_fp_", Sys.Date(), sep=''))
     
     # Facetted barcharts
     setwd(config$scripts_dir_local)
     rmarkdown::render('./Barcharts/Barcharts_fp_facet.Rmd',output_file = paste(config$results_dir_local, "/barcharts_fp_facet_", Sys.Date(), sep=''))
     
     # Make a bubble plot
     setwd(config$scripts_dir_local)
     rmarkdown::render('./Bubbleplots/Bubbleplots_fp.Rmd',output_file = paste(config$results_dir_local, "/bubbleplots_fp_", Sys.Date(), sep=''))
